*143. Electric vehicles & India* 
‚Ä¢ Will help reduce pollution & GHG emissions. 
‚Ä¢ Framework has been set by the government for faster adoption. Companies like Ather & Okinawa are involved electric vehicle manufacturing in India. 
‚Ä¢ Indian landscape is different in way that it the market should focus on 2/3 wheelers & buses more than cars. Penetration is still low in Indian market.  

Challenges: 
‚Ä¢ Charging Infrastructure: very much important for persuasion to consumers to go for electric vehicles. However, for 2/3 wheelers ‚Äì Charging would be home based. 
‚Ä¢ Flyby operators - importing junk Chinese tech & assembling it here - not a dumping ground 
‚Ä¢ Federal Structure ‚Äì Multiple policies in National & State level. 

Government Steps: 
‚Ä¢ National electric mobility mission plan 2020:  providing the vision and the roadmap for the faster adoption of electric vehicles and their manufacturing in the country 
‚Ä¢ FAME-II: faster adoption & Manufacturing of electric & hybrid vehicles in India. 
‚Ä¢ Creating demand Incentives
    o Reduced cost to consumers 
    o Fiscal & non fiscal incentives by state governments. 
    o Additional income tax deduction Rs. 1.5 lakh to purchase electric vehicles
    o GST from 12 ‚Äì 5%
‚Ä¢ Establishment of charging stations: also interlinking of renewable energy sources with charging infrastructure, smart grid. 
‚Ä¢ Phased manufacturing: demand incentive linked to domestic products, battery mfg - sunrise industry

Way Forward: 
‚Ä¢ Administration of scheme including publicity, IEC(Information, education & communication) activities. 
‚Ä¢ Out of the box / non-monetary incentives ‚Äì free parking for electric vehicles, reimbursement of toll tax on highways. 
‚Ä¢ Reimagining the role of startups in this sector to meet the domestic consumption & be a global leader ‚Äì Smart, shared & Connected technology.  
‚Ä¢ R&D ‚Äì investment in research is very important to explore different battery technologies - Li-ion, fuel cell, Li ‚Äì phosphate. Ambient temperatures of battery is important & India is a hot compared to rest of the world. 
‚Ä¢ Awareness for consumers to understand the technology & also the need.
‚Ä¢ Streamlined policy throughout the country & a bottom up approach ‚Äì understanding the need of consumers addressing their concerns.
What you think about this step by Pakistani government?? Or any point that you have in your mind, i always appreciate suggestions.

Such sobering news!  Though not quite pro-nuke, I also had doubts about solar after learning of rooftop solar panel problems from my siblings living in California and Nevada.  At that time, I was living in a one-story 1500 sq. ft. non-solar home surrounded by trees on nearly an acre plot of land in suburban Athens, Georgia.  After comparing my monthly utility bill with theirs, I realized the immense benefits of living the simpler life--that is, not having to worry about cleaning bird poop and pollen/dust build-up on and under solar panels, plus not having to monitor solar cell efficiencies, etc.  And if my siblings are any indication, with lowered utility bills, people living on renewable energy are just going to find other ways to INCREASE their household energy consumption, such as using more AC, installing ostentatious fountains with pumps, greener lawns, etc.

People need to realize the ‚Äòclimate crisis‚Äô is being grossly over exaggerated.
For example, the widely reported number of 97% of scientists agreeing that humans are responsible for climate change is a lie. Do you know how that number was derived? It‚Äôs based on a 2013 analysis by John Cook of around 12,000 global climate change papers. None were read in full, only the abstract / summary paragraphs were reviewed and then grouped into one of 4 categories:
1. 3,896 papers agreed that humans were to blame for climate change.
2. 7,930 took no position either way.
3. 78 rejected the idea of humans being to blame.
4. 40 we‚Äôre uncertain altogether.
That initial pass gave only 32% stating global warming was down to anthropological activity. Cook‚Äôs team didn‚Äôt think that was anywhere near alarming enough, so the 7,930 papers that held no position either way were removed from the final analysis. This gave a much more ‚Äòacceptable‚Äô result of 97% of papers that now agreed with the desired result of the exercise, which Obama and John Kerry then decided to broadcast as ‚Äò97% of all scientists agree that humans are responsible for climate change‚Äô.
This is what ‚Äòthe consensus is that nearly all climate scientists agree that humans are responsible for climate change‚Äô is based on.
Ideological and political groups are manipulating the public fear response for their own purposes of control.
Modern environmental data gathering techniques repeatedly demonstrate that the models used for prediction used by environmental groups are over stating the rate of change by around a factor of 2.0-2.5. They additionally underestimate the amount of heat loss from the atmosphere into space by a factor of 6.
CO2 is also demonized as a toxin, yet all plant life on Earth needs it to survive. Forests, jungles and crop harvests are growing and improving world wide.
The only observable potential issue is sea level rise, which has been around 1.9mm per year on average over the last 125 years and is a perfectly manageable rate of change. Sea level change has been a constant variable throughout Earths history and will continue to go up and down.

Intellectual honesty is increasingly rare to behold. The irony to me is that I'm "just a philosopher," yet I've been trying to convey these exact points to other-field "experts" for many years, always to be told that "philosophers aren't experts in any field" and so dismissed by "the experts" in the "relevant" fields. How much directional entropy have we developed over the decades of touting renewables that we must now overcome? How much political commitment (and promises made that must be kept) is there that even the (now) "experts" are (finally) coming to realize must be overcome?

The problem with intellectual honesty is that most fields actually don't have it. Science in particular is very, very slow to correct its falsified directions/commitments! And most scientists today still believe in the absolutely debunked verificationism codified in the 50s as "positivism." This is sold to the public as "studies show," "science has shown," "follow the science," and other such catchy phrases that lead the public (who pays for the research) to believe that science is telling us the "facts of the universe" rather than the actual thing it is telling us: "This is how things seem to work to us at this moment, not taking the various anomalies into account that will perhaps [essentially certainly] end up falsifying our present perspectives/models." And so, "predictive results" stand equivalent to "metaphysical results," when in fact they bear no resemblance to each other.

Meanwhile, the general public is led around by the nose (always paying for it), as we hear "follow the science," yet the vast, VAST majority of people (including the vast majority of scientists themselves) have precisely zero idea what "science" even IS.

Don't get me wrong! I'm not a "science basher." Far from it! I'll go to an MD over a witch doctor any day of the week! And I'll respect nuclear physics over rubbing sticks together to see what might happen any day of the week! Science gets us microwave ovens and space shuttles that don't blow up most of the time. But it's NOT doing metaphysics, which, unfortunately, is how science is marketed to the public that pays for it. So, science (and how its results are marketed) should be MUCH less strident and confident in its theories and results; and that means it should be MUCH less culpable in even obliquely FORCING people to "follow the science" or be considered a quaint whack job!

It's absolutely incorrect to say, "There's much that science doesn't yet know." It is instead accurate to say, "There is nothing that science knows... unless you are deflating the value of the word 'know' quite significantly." Even the idea that "the best evidence" is summed up by the present slate of "scientific knowledge" is giving empirical "knowledge" itself far too much credit. And this present video just scratches the surface of making that very point!

There is NO knowledge that is not rife with interpretation and a pre-existing web of beliefs that have more or less justification for each thread of that complex web. The problem with "national science" and "follow the science" is that those phrases "justify" (falsely so-called) forming national policy (and exercising force against dissenters) on the basis of whatever a present group of "experts" happen to believe at the moment. And, as we are now finally starting to discover in the subject of this very video, distinguishing preferences and politics from the ACTUAL science is essentially impossible! Even who are counted as the "experts" is so laden with interpretation and the foibles of the scientific method itself, not to mention preferences, cronyism, and politics, that the whole mess becomes a self-replicating monster at the national level.

You'd think that we would eventually learn from our perpetually-repeated mistake. But, as I led with, intellectual honesty is a very rare character attribute!

If EV vehicles were not so expensive I would be all aboard, but even a certified preowned Tesla with low mileage is $50K. I looked online and found that the average price from Tesla for a replacement battery pack cost between $13K-$14K. That means if I go out and find a 2012 or 2013 Model S for sale preowned for about $25K-$30K that is on the verge of needing a new battery pack and a short period of time after purchasing the car the battery pack fails, I would be out of another $13K-$14K for a new battery pack on top of what I paid or financed for the price of the car. I would burn that stupid car in the street and claim it as a insurance lost vs fixing it. I think if manufacturers want us or force us the consumers to go green then there should be a lifetime warranty on the the battery pack. I believe if EV vehicles help the environment as much as the experts state then why should we have to pay for a new battery pack if I was driving a "green" vehicle and it's good for the environment? Maybe there can be a future federal law passed or a rebate of some sort to where if the battery pack does go bad then the owner would only pay the labor for the needed repairs or a reduced price vs the current price. I would definitely consider going green if some of these service were reduced, but I refuse to spend that amount of money on a car to where after years of owing it I would be better off buying a whole different car for the amount of a replacement battery pack. That is one topic I wish was covered in this video. The long term ownership cost and long term value of a EV vehicle vs the long term ownership cost and long term value of a internal combustion vehicle.

The initial cost of electric vehicles and the lack of government incentives in Ontario are going to make the conversion from gasoline a slower process than anticipated.  First, you must be in the small category of people who purchase their vehicles new.  Throughout my fifty year driving career, I have never purchased a NEW vehicle, always purchased used.  Would you purchase a used (5 year old) Chevy VOLT that has only 3 to 5 years left of battery life and knowing that a 32 cent diode failure could render the vehicle useless?  In most cases,  those shopping for an EV are homeowners, who have a dedicated driveway or garage for overnight parking and charging.  Your home electrical panel will require costly modifications and charging equipment to allow the vehicle to be trickle charged overnight and more costly to "quick charge" from your home.  It is not reasonable to own an electric vehicle if you need to rely on the limited number of quick charging stations that are currently available .   Throughout Toronto, for example, there are many, many thousands of vehicles that rely on overnight street parking without a dedicated parking spot.  On night you manage to park in front of your house, the next night you park in front of your neighbour's house six doors down and the next night you park around the corner on the next block.  If fifty percent of all vehicles today were EVs and they all plugged in overnight, the Ontario power grid would come crashing down.  We already suffer blackouts and brownouts during hot summer months when home air conditioning units are running.  The upgrades to the electrical grid to support electric vehicles will not be cheap and the cost of electricity,  which we use for a multitude of purposes, is going to sky rocket.  The future savings of operating an electric vehicle are very questionable.   Conversion to electric vehicles can certainly provide an enormous benefit to the environment, but only if very strategic smart planning is managed between the competing energy sectors and all levels of government.....but, When did you last see that happen?

The prediction that it will take till 2040 to get EVs moving in large numbers is complete rubbish. The number of chargers is increasing fast. This stuff is not linear. It's exponential.

2) Time to charge. I can handle 30 minutes or so to get most of my charge, but most of the time it looks like we're talking about an hour or more ‚Äì IF you're talking about a higher end charger. Most other places allow for topping off type charges, if that.
3) Access to charging. If I want to visit relations in northeast Iowa or northern Lower Michigan, I don't want to have to worry about driving an hour or so to the nearest charger (next to an interstate, of course) to fully recharge my vehicle...nor do I want to nurse what charge I have (between top off style charges) if I spend a week in and around NE Iowa (which is the present situation).
4) I rent an apartment without garages, so I can't recharge overnight while I sleep. There is a limited amount of access to chargers where I live. Even if EV chargers won't be as ubiquitous as gas stations are nowadays (which I understand fully ‚Äì if you can charge at home, you'll happily charge at home), they need to be around for travelers, people on a night out, commuters and those of us without direct access to charging.
5: Today's EVs are designed to stand out. From what I can see the Korean EVs are the only EVs (outside the Rivian, and they sort of push the envelope) that look like a normal vehicle at first glance. I wish to see more EV that don't stand out from regular cars (of course, the EV style may end up winning out. I just don't see THAT happening as of right now).

Now, I believe that EVs are the future. I just don't believe the future is quite here yet, and if that means I'm late to the party so be it ‚Äì at least the EV tech will be worked out by then.

Why? 
(1) Upfront cost.  Yes, I know total cost of ownership is less in the long run,  but few buyers consider that.
(2) Range/infrastructure (unless you have a Tesla).  Actually, a car with 150 mile range would work for 99% of car buyers IF charging stations were less than 150 miles apart and there were more than one charger per location.  But they're not (unless you have a Tesla).  You can drive from just west of Detroit (Ann Arbor) to just east of Chicago (Hammond, IN) along I-94 and find ONE , I repeat ONE, DCFC charging station.
(3) This one wasn't mentioned - availability.  The only EVs available NATIONALLY in the U.S. are the Teslas, the Chevy Bolt and the 40kw version of the Nissan LEAF.  The rest are "compliance cars", only available in California and a handful of other states with draconian environmental regulations.  
(4) And yes, dealers don't want to sell them because there's little service income, which is what keeps them in business.

One of the things I learned from being a paralegal is something car rentals want to hide from you is that in California (check for your own state) it is the vehicle owner's responsibility to procure primary liability insurance. This includes car rental companies. In other words, you, as a permissive user, are automatically covered by the rental company for BASIC LIABILTY minimum limits (15/30/5) and, according to state law, are not required to purchase additional coverage. Furthermore, if you do purchase additional coverage (which is not legally required), there can be no claim made on your additional coverage until the car rental company's coverage is exhausted. That's why it's called "primary". I have even been lied to at the time of renting a car, as the rep told me that they don't insure there cars. Interestingly enough, when I sat down in the car I had just rented (and didn't insure), I saw a sticker on the windshield indicating the companies self-insurance (which is insurance) administrator service that I need to contact if I was involved in an accident. PLEASE NOTE THAT THIS IS NOT LEGAL ADVISE. I'M MERELY GIVING INFORMATION AND NOT SUGGUSTING ANY ACTION OR INACTION FOR ANYONE TO TAKE OR NOT TAKE.

Another huge tip that A LOT of people don‚Äôt think about is if you live in a city with multiple of the same car rental branches, search for the best price then transfer it.

Insurance is weird and unpredictable with so many variables and provisos that it is impossible for one person to guarantee that one company is always cheaper than another, or that one thing is more expensive to insure than another.  It might cost me much more to insure the exact same model of car than my neighbour because of all kinds of personal circumstances.  It might be much cheaper to insure a certain model with a certain insurance company than a similar model with the same or different company. Maybe I could insure a Tesla for less than it would cost you to insure a Zoe.  It might cost less next week or next month ... or more!  I honestly think insurers pluck figures out of the air depending on who you are, what you want, and how badly they want your business. So, in other words, "Your Mileage May Vary"!

Hi EVM, interesting video for me as an EV owner and a qualified insurance broker who has been in the industry for nearly 15 years.

You raise some good points, some of which are not entirely accurate. I like the way you looked at risk comparing the EV and Petrol counterparts stating that your not comparing like for like or "apples to apples". However, whilst comparing list prices with list prices, remember that these vehicles devalue at different rates. My understanding is that typically, EV's devalue faster than ICE vehicles. You'd be hard pressed to find an insurer who will replace your vehicle with a list priced brand new car after a total loss claim once the car is more than six months old, although, you can purchase GAP insurance to cover this.

Whilst you are right in stating that the LV policy seems like some fluffy marketing to sell more insurance to EV owners (things like this happen all the time), there are potential benefits from the policy given your points raised (please note, I am not an employee of LV or associated with LV). For example, your point about the household insurance and the wall box being covered by it. This assumes that there is a household policy in place to cover the wall box. My wall box is outside and some HH insurers may exclude cover for contents which are permanently outside. It's also my understanding that more people insure their pets than they insure their homes (which is bonkers but that might be because I'm a cold hearted insurance broker by trade). Also, whilst you may pay ¬£150 to replace your wall box and do it yourself, I wouldn't. I know hardly anything about electrics so I would pay an electrician to come out and replace it. Granted, this maybe a minimum cost of ¬£60 which would still fall under an assumed excess of ¬£250 (my excess is ¬£150 on my car), due to my circumstances, the cost to install my car charging setup was over ¬£800 (my circumstances are not typical and it took about 6 hours to install by a qualified electrician). Also, if your already claiming on car insurance, a lot of which come with protected no claims discount, why would you claim on household insurance for the wall box?

If you wanted to into more detail, I'd be happy to discuss this with you.

I hate to broach into politics, but I do wonder if issues like discussed in this video are going to lead over time to big divides in EV adoption rates between the blue states and red states. I just cannot see a state like Texas ever passing a Right to Charge law (the oil and gas lobby will make sure of that), so in a red state, the only way to charge at home will be to buy a single-family house, with no HOA to get in the way.

I contacted my HOA for approval to install my level 2 charger in the garage of my condo before buying my Bolt EV. It was no problem. No extra insurance. I had an electrician do the work. Does this mean we should be concerned if we have a 240V dryer?

I agree that HOAs seem restrictive. They should let people install chargers if the owner is willing to pay for it (because it is way more economical to install a charger than buy gas). I disagree that HOA's should be mandated to install chargers though, because they would simply turn around and charge everyone more, even the people who don't need it, which could cause needless animosity.

Another unique and good report from Eric.  In Walnut Creek's  Rossmoor community, there is a large "mutual" (not quite an HOA) that simultaneously went after EV chargers in garages by imposing ridiculous fees ($10K?) and made complex and costly rules for solar panel installations.   Then the management corp. installed large banks of Level 2 EVSEs at busy locations (good), but limited EV-only access to early AM hours meaning the spaces are usually ICEd.

The irony of the HOA, is that the longer the HOA exists, the more percentage of its income goes towards legal collections for fines and fees. The general concept of an HOA is akin to a snake that eventually eats its own tail.  This is probably why they want this liability insurance payment, cuz they are constantly looking for new sources of income to maintain their existence.

Leasing can be broken down into a very simple question. In this case, after 36 months, do you want to retain options or obligations? Options come at a cost but for most they are well worth it. Nothing is worse than owing 36 more months on a car that has worn out its welcome especially if it's been problematic. Your warranty for most makes, will have expired and you're on your own. Well worth the additional $1200 to $1700 to  avoid a scenario where you're out of warranty staring at three more years of payments, assuming you're keeping the vehicle.

I've never paid over $6000 for any vehicle I've driven. I always buy private party or at an auction. Overall my vehicles have been very reliable and my cars generally look presentable. I've often sold cars for more than I paid for them. My total cost to own vehicles (not including fuel cost) for the past 20 years has been less than most people pay for one single car. Going this route does mean you have to take ownership and interest in your vehicle and vehicles in general. I've had to learn how to fix many things myself, which makes and models are reliable and sought after, how to buy and sell cars, where to find the best deals on parts, and where to get good used parts for high ticket items (transmissions etc). I know it's not for everyone, but the tens of thousands of dollars I've saved have been well worth any extra hassle or time I've spent. This "extreme ownership" style of acquiring and keeping vehicles has given me more hands-on skills, mechanical acumen, common sense, business knowledge, and genuine pleasure than all of my formal education and most of my hobbies combined.

The first comparison you draw - keep scenario between buying vs leasing - is actually closer to a wash...in fact, it may be "more economical" as you put it because all your figures are in today's dollars.  If you are having to make payments, you want to give the least amount of money up-front as possible because, unless serial payments are being made (which they are not because the payments are fixed across the three years), it behooves you to lease because tomorrow's dollars are worth less than today's due to inflation.  I know this adds a layer of complexity, but you would need to respectively discount the future cash outflows between the two options, and I believe when you do that, the lease option comes out ahead when you factor inflation into the calculation.

Leases are a great way to learn to never want another lease.  

A minor scrape becomes a major nightmare.  If you fix it, and don't tell your lease holder, then it costs lots of money, and likely won't be undetectable (leaseholder will find it, and tack on a fee at the end).  If you don't fix it, then it might rust and the lease holder will assess even more than what it might cost to fix today.  And if you tell the lease holder, they will punish you twice by giving you the option of "letting" them fix it (at stealership rates), or roll the dice on the above fix/or no fix.  Either way, they know the damage was done so they will be adding a fee at the end, no matter what.  So the only "smart" choice is to make sure you get it fixed so well that nobody can tell (impossible..?), and hope to avoid detection. 

 These little nighmares, in addition to mileage limits, make leases like borrowing a glass vase from the Queen. 

 Just too much downside when real life happens.

The way you maintain your car is unlikely to change whether you lease or buy so it's smarter to make any overlooked repairs the problem of the manufacturer. If you have the credit for it and aren't under extreme budget constraints, I'll suggest a no down payment lease including all your taxes and fees rolled in. Give or take, it's an average of an additional 50bucks or less in monthly payment but protects you from losing your down payment in the scenario of a total loss etc. Understand your driving habits in terms of mileage so you can negotiate the right miles upfront so you don't go over and pay penalties OR feel restricted while leasing the car.

Buying is really for those who have no real desire to swap cars often especially not in 3years and have the means to pay a higher monthly payment. In order to maintain the value of the car as close to the desired value as possible, it requires meticulous maintenance routine and record keeping as well as the willingness to sell a car as a private party. Additionally, you have to be willing to assume the risks of being liable for any after-purchase issues and the buyer potentially knowing where you live, work or who you are in order to complete the sale. Financially, any equity you have in buying a car is at constant risk of depreciation due to market forces like public perception of the car, unforeseen issues that may arise after the purchase ie recalls, faulty parts and design, popularity of the model or the vehicles sales performance after release etc. In the current era of frequently updated body styles and models, the appetite for one model becoming a classic or even desirable is very low because manufacturers are constantly updating vehicles with new technology in order to make the new models sellable and appealing. From experience in the industry, buying has to be the choice of very decisive people who are extremely certain of keeping the car for a minimum of 5years in order for it to payoff. Meaning you can use it as a bad form of savings in case you need cash from a physical property you own. 

There's more to it than what I've explained above but for all intents and purposes, and from my experience in the industry, leasing is the superior choice financially.

You didn't account for two things that swings the Lease as favorable, even in your "keep" the car scenario:
1.)  Deferment of Sales Tax.  For a Buy, you have pay/finance all the sales tax into the loan.  For a lease, you pay it monthly.  Meaning, in a Buy, you are paying interest on 100% of the sales tax, where a lease, you are paying the sales tax monthly, and then bulk at the end.  (If you live in a state with no sales tax (there's a handful), then you lose that advantage of course.)
2.)  Subvented Rates.  In the scenario where 0% financing is offered, you are correct that for a Buy, the low APR is in lieu of rebates, so you're essentially losing the rebate to take advantage of the 0%.  In Leases, however, that is not the case, the Rebates on a lease are in conjunction with any low money factor (lease equivalent of an APR).

You also put the "Buy" at 36 Months, when anything under 60 months is incredibly rare.  A fairer comparison would be to make the buy for 60 Months, and then make the Lease for 36 Months, plus finance the Residual for the last 24 Months (and bump the residual finance rate up a bit since you're financing a used car at that point).  I realize that would make for a more complex video, so I can appreciate sticking to the simpler scenario.

This is very general and the problem is you are missing some very critical factors that can greatly influence and drive up or down what you pay out of pocket.  On a lease,  interest is expressed as a "money factor" which appears as a decimal on your lease contract. You would not know what your true interest rate is, and thus how much of your monthly payment is interest versus depreciation, unless you can convert the money factor to the interest rate.  Your lease payment is mostly comprised of depreciation and interest which is the rent charge or finance fee.  It is still a loan, and the bank is going to charge you for the use of their money.  The onus is on you to understand the math and the numbers because they are not going to explain it to you.  You will get cross-eyed looking at a lease contract that is about two and a half feet long.  99% of customers will not bother to read through and dissect the numbers.

A couple of other things. First of all if you lease a luxury brand like a BMW, the terms of the lease require you to maintain it and they are going to know if you haven't maintained it. Other brands might or might not be the same. You can't just say I'm gonna lease because I don't like having to maintain cars. Scheduled maintenance may be included but you still have to do it. Second of all, a bigger problem is that when a lease is up, you're under pressure to do something with the car. It may be a bad time for you to do that. You might be busy or you might be short on funds or you might be waiting for the newer model. They may let you continue leasing month to month but if you go back into that dealership they're going to know you need to do something because your lease is up. You don't have as much leverage. Third, insurance is higher if you lease. Fourth, you can refinance your car loan. I had a 4.25% rate which was low for 2nd quarter 2019 but 1st quarter 2020, my credit union had a 0.9% offer. Fifth, you're stuck with the car. Ever have buyer's remorse? I have. In December 2018, I bought a truck. Decided it wasn't for me. I really didn't like it at all. 6 months later I sold it for an $800 profit. And this was a new truck mind you. With a lease you're heavily penalized if you want out.

Such arrogance on display in this video! One would think no other country has an auto industry that matters! Let's run through some of the claims:
*Germany "dominates" the auto industry. Provably false. While it is true that Volkswagen is the #1 manufacturer, it is almost entirely due to acquisitions and mergers in the past 10 years. Ford was the largest car company during the first 20 years of the auto revolution, GM overtook it and remained #1 for the next 80 years, and then Toyota became the largest for most of the past decade. In any case, Germany has NEVER ranked #1 in production. China currently is the largest, with 25,000,000 autos made in 2020. The US is second with almost 9,000,000 in 2020. Japan is third with 8,000,000 in 2020. Germany's production was less than 4,000,000. The US was the largest manufacturer of autos for most of the 20th century and the first decade of the 21st. Japan was #1 in production for a number of years in the mid-1980's to mid-1990's. Neither ever came close to China's record of almost 30,000,000 produced in 2017. 
*The video appears to suggest that Germany is the leader of auto technology. Provably untrue. GM, Toyota, Ford, and Honda are the top 4 companies with the largest technology patent portfolios in force globally. In 2019, both GM and Toyota patented over 1,000 new inventions each. US firms are the patent leaders in driverless, self-parking, camera, remote start, and power accessory technologies. 
*German cars are "perfect" and/or "perfectly" engineered. A ludicrous claim. Nothing human beings do is ever 100% perfect all the time. 
*No one else comes close to Germany's auto industry. Did he REALLY state that?? In what way does he mean? Size? Quality? Durability? Performance? Car companies usually cannot do all of those at once! It is very difficult to build a "durable" supercar or a "luxury" SUV that is also very tough. If judging durability, Germany  is not the leader. Where Is Greta Thunberg? 

It seems as though the world is on the fast lane toward cleaning the car industry from polluting emissions. Everyone is rushing to create clean cars, whether battery or hydrogen powered engines, and bask in their cleanness.
But the green alibi hides behind it a dirty truth: Zero emission does not mean zero pollution. Mining rare Earth materials required for zero-emissions engines, building charging stations, and the complex logistics surrounding the ‚Äúclean‚Äù industries will take a heavy toll on Earth. In the end, the only ones who will gain from the ‚Äúclean revolution‚Äù are the tycoons who are selling it to us, and the government officials who placate them for their own reasons.
Where is Greta Thunberg these days? Like the rest of the pawns in the battle for wealth and power, the ‚Äúclimate knights‚Äù have sent her back to oblivion once they finished using her. It is all power games among giant corporations, but the environment and the climate are no one‚Äôs concern.
Even if we switch to wind energy or ocean-wave energy, I don‚Äôt believe that we will gain much. We will have to pay for it elsewhere.
For this reason, I think that the crux of the problem is not emissions, but our behavior toward nature and toward our fellow human beings. Here is where we can produce positive and lasting results. If we could communicate with one another positively, we could stop the madness of excessive development that manufactures unnecessary and harmful products.
If we could slow down a bit, we wouldn‚Äôt need to burn so much fuel in order to defeat competitors in a race for wealth that makes no one happy. Only if we realize that our happiness depends on the quality of our relationships, and not on the padding of our bank accounts, we will be able to pause a little, think, and rebuild our civilization in a way that contributes to nature, to humanity, and to each of us.

Consumers' free choice is what pulls cars through the automakers' supply chains.  I've never seen propaganda from any company that says gasoline is better than electricity; That's a silly notion which can only be held by people who don't want to honestly scrutinize their beliefs for weaknesses.  German automakers do make electric cars, arguably some of the best in the world, as well as many engines with fuel efficiency and performance that people couldn't even imagine was possible a few decades ago, which has certainly helped out the environment compared to the mission to destroy the environment that they're being accused of.
Consumers generally don't buy electric cars because electric cars lose in a direct comparison with alternatives.  In my case, if I bought an affordable electric car, it would cost more than a GTI for none of the performance, I have no way of charging it in its outdoor parking space, it would always be wasting energy keeping the battery pack warm to hold a charge when it's cold outside, and I'd be limited in where I could travel compared to a gasoline car.  I'm not even sure it would be better for the environment, considering the energy required to make a car can be more than the energy the car uses in its full lifetime of driving.  
The cost/performance of batteries is really what's holding electric cars back.  There aren't unseen forces conspiring against the advancement of this technology, it just takes time to improve like every other technology.  Arguably, a truly good electricity storage technology for automotive has yet to be invented even, so throwing money at improving lithium isn't a very effective plan for automakers.  
When the electric car has the same performance and is cheaper than combustion (which is also steadily improving), then people and companies will find ways to overcome any other obstacles to making electric cars the default choice.  Nobody will oppose it.  Car companies actually like making products that consumers want to buy

‚Ä¢	Mission Statement: This describes what an organization does, its primary purpose, or its reason for existence. It focuses on the present and is more about the ‚Äúhow‚Äù. A mission statement typically answers the question, ‚ÄúWhat do we do?‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Vision Statement: This describes where the organization sees itself in the future or what it wants to become. It‚Äôs aspirational and provides a long-term outlook. A vision statement answers the question, ‚ÄúWhere do we want to be?‚Äù

In terms of sequence:

	‚Ä¢	Vision usually comes first. It sets the long-term direction and aspiration. It‚Äôs the ‚Äúbig picture‚Äù of what the organization hopes to achieve in the future.
	‚Ä¢	Mission follows the vision. Once the organization has a clear vision of the future, the mission defines how it will get there. It‚Äôs the actionable part that guides daily operations and decisions.

I bought a 2015 Jeep Wrangler from Carmax. Carmax has its pros and cons. Their 30 day return policy, for a full refund no questions asked, is a significant incentive to do business with them. I‚Äôm unaware of any other used car dealer offering anything like that. They also offer a 24 hour test drive. 

They claim every vehicle is fully inspected and any necessary repairs are done. Former employees indicate that is true.  They openly acknowledge they charge more for their vehicles than the typical used car dealer and undervalue potential trade vehicles. Are their additional cost worth the potential benefits they offer? Customers have to decide that for themselves. 

In my case I got a preowned Jeep that was in like new condition inside and out that clearly had been well taken care of by the original owner. Ten Jeeps with the same trim levels, same model year, would sell for different prices based on the condition and mileage of each Jeep. Based on that, I paid a fair, maybe even good, price for the Jeep I got at Carmax. I‚Äôm a satisfied Carmax customer.

They charged me a couple hundreds dollars to ship it half way across the country, which seemed fair.  There was a slight upcharge on the car compared to other local spots (~5% in my case), but it was still within the fair KBB market value.  And they gave me a little more on my trade in than anyone else for whatever reason, so that helped wipe out most of the difference.  

Then you get that 24 hour test drive and 30 day money back guarantee, which gives you plenty of time to get it checked out by a mechanic and run the piss out of it to make sure it's a solid car with no duck tape holding it together.

Fact checks: 1) Carmax is transparent with the history of the vehicles they sell. Go to their website and every vehicle listed has the history available. They use Experian's AutoCheck. NOTHING is hidden. 2) Yes, Carfax and AutoCheck may not be 100% accurate but they are the same sources used by every other dealer or seller of used vehicles, as well as buyers. 3) Carmax has a 7 day return policy. You can test drive a vehicle for a whole week, have it checked out by one or more mechanics and if you are not satisfied and the vehicle is not damaged Carmax will take the vehicle back within the seven day period, no questions asked. 4) I have purchased rental cars and have had no issues. Rental cars are maintained regularly and kept in good condition and usually have low miles 5) It is Carmax's policy to not sell cars with frame damage. If a car should slip through their quality audit for frame damage they have taken the car back. 6) Regular dealers are notorious for their used car warranty - 30 seconds or 30 miles, whichever comes first. Carmax vehicles have a 90 day, 4K mile limited warranty. And I do not believe private sellers offer any warranty. 
Pricing is a function of the value provided. Carmax may have premium pricing but they offer haggle free transactions, vast selection and peace of mind. I declined an offer for my Mazda from Carmax for a price that I thought was $1K too low. It took me six months, many test drives and a whole lot of running around to finally sell the car for about $250 more than I could have sold it to Carmax. So it depends on how much an individual values their time and effort. 
You may speculate that I am an employee or have some connection to Carmax, but I do not. Carmax is not perfect and I do not appreciate the hard sell on their extended service plans. In this respect they are no different  than all sellers of extended service plans for automobiles or anything else. Profit margins are substantial on extended service plans and very profitable, but in most cases not beneficial for the consumer,

1) Check out the cars in the Consumer Reports Auto Issue to find which cars to buy and which ones to run away from. They are the most honest authority, since they do surveys of car owners and what problems they encountered and if they liked their car enough to buy it again. 
2) Arrange your financing before car shopping. Credit Unions sometimes give the best rates. If your credit is bad, save up cash and buy a older used car from an individual, but have it checked out by a trusted mechanic first. 
3) If buying from a regular car dealer, go at the end of the month. Salesmen and the dealer get bonuses for sales, so they lower their prices to move 'em out as an incentive. 
4) Scotty is right about this, Don't buy a new car unless you plan on keeping it for 5 years or longer. Depreciation will kill the car's value the first 3-4 years. 
5) Do your due diligence beforehand and you might come out ahead of the game.

Here are some questions/concerns i've. Please clarify, if you're ignorant about these .?

1. If a disaster strikes or a war happens, a nuclear power plant becomes a time bomb. Wherever disaster struck, people have not gone back to live there. Check Chernobyl, Fukushima online.
When accidents happen in other places, people in the factory die, its a one time incident, normal life resumes but here whole towns and villages are vacated permanently and effects will be felt for generations.

2. The water that's used to cool the reactors is pumped back to the sea. It's super hot when it goes back. This spoils marine life and the fishermen who depend on it near it's vicinity.

3. AFR literally means Away From Reactor. Govt wants to build this disposal plant in koodankulam it self. Why didn't you speak of it, when mentioning the issue in koodankulam.

4. Hydro isn't clean. If we generate power from running water using the same dynamo set up, as in gravity light, it's clean. If it's using large dams it's not. It can create landslides when near hills, which it is always. It upsets the balance in nature's design. Also it stops minerals and nutrients from the hills reaching the fields. These deposits over years can increase the acidity of water. Even if it's rare, it's a possibility.

4. If we connect rivers like in the past via ground it's acceptable. Because it recharges water table along the way. But these projects offer to build concrete channels. It only benefits the big corporations that build it.

Points 4 & 5 affects marine life. Not that we'll care.

6. Most of our clean power is coming from windmills. You can see the effects of it in Radhapuram district. Before windmills arrived, it was a lush forest with following streams. Now it's a desert. Some people travel 16 km for water. Check google earth and you'll see the desert that it has become. So depending on application it becomes clean or unclean. This is why smarter countries keep it in the ocean.

7. The most abundant natural power available to us is sun. It's a cleaner form. All house roofs in urban areas can have it. Excess power can be given back to grid. Why not speak more on that.

8. Agreed power need is more. But clean solution lies in decentralising power, not centralising power through dams and nuclear plants.

G‚Äôday again Chris.
I‚Äôve just had a good lengthy drive of the Kona, (well two drives today actually) and have to confess that I‚Äôm shocked!

I drove the Kona when I dropped off our PHEV this morning for a service - quite literally the first from the public to drive it at our local dealer. Even the dealer hasn‚Äôt driven it since the Sydney reveal a few months ago.
Initial impressions, very good, and (quite honestly) very bad in some areas.

Power? Great, but VERY inclined to chirp or spin the front wheels, and LOTS and LOTS of torque steer when you plant it hard. It will absolutely chew through front tyres if driven hard. I can‚Äôt begin to imagine how it would be a wet road. The power ‚Äúcurve‚Äù through the accelerator sensitivity at some speeds seemed off, a tad hard to control and not at all smooth. (Our PHEV is much smoother, though of course much less power on tap, and my recollection from my three Tesla drives, including an S for a whole weekend, was also much smoother.) 
I love the variable flappy paddle regen, and do dearly wish the Tesla‚Äôs had that. After getting used to it on the PHEV, I will definitely miss it.

Driving seat and dash- mostly good, though ‚Äúfussy‚Äù and quite involved, even somewhat unintuitive getting through the multiple menu‚Äôs. I love Tesla‚Äôs KISS principle, like an iPhone compared to using Windows. Strangely the test car is a basic model called ‚Äúlaunch‚Äù edition, and had a different, significantly smaller screen on the centre of the dash to either the Elite or Highlander, so not truly representative of what‚Äôs now on sale.
Great ride, compared to the petrol Kona which is quite harsh and choppy by comparison.

The battery hangs very low, and I‚Äôd be VERY scared about damaging it on dirt roads or with debris on the highway. Basically if I saw anything on the road, I‚Äôd want to avoid it at all costs.
Rear seat leg room- absolutely bloody terrible, might be Ok with a short driver. (I‚Äôm 187cm.) After driving it for a while and getting the seat in the proper driving position, it was virtually physically impossible for me to get in the rear seat through a half open door (due to cars parked beside us, typical of a shopping centre car park.) Leg room was really terrible, almost non existent! When I eventually squeezed in, my head was touching the roof liner.
Thus the rear seat adjusted for a taller driver might be ok for maybe a five year old, (even though they‚Äôd whinge), and not much older!


The ‚Äúlane keep assist‚Äù autopilot feature on the test car was worse than useless, refused to work with shadows on the road then just barely worked ‚Äúping pong‚Äù style when there were no shadows. It was nowhere near as good as the RAV4 hire car we had in England last year.
Basically a massive disappointment, a massive fail.
However after a bit of further research, I‚Äôm genuinely shocked. It turns out that here in Oz  üá¶üá∫ , we get only ‚Äúlane keep assist‚Äù, which is almost useless. In the UK and Europe, all the video reviews you‚Äôll see have both ‚Äúlane keep assist‚Äù AND ‚Äúlane follow assist‚Äù. On the UK website, that‚Äôs on both their mid and top spec models. The difference is night and day, with the latter (ie: Euro spec) being a basic autopilot, the former meaning you‚Äôll just ping-pong down the road, maybe if you‚Äôre lucky. I found it often did nothing at all.

Adaptive cruise control is pretty much like any other car with that feature, and can actually be used with the ‚Äúadaptive‚Äù function turned off,  perhaps could be useful occasionally, unlike many other cars which are ‚Äúall or none‚Äù. It has the usual problems like slowing dramatically for a car turning left in front of you, or cutting into your lane.

How much? Too much, a few hundred dollars change out of $70k for the Highlander. - The Elite doesn‚Äôt even have LED headlights!

I‚Äôm shocked about the lack of ‚Äúlane keep follow‚Äù, a total 100% deal breaker even ignoring 


After that drive this morning, and then another this afternoon with my wife, I‚Äôm honestly more convinced than ever about a Model 3.

Following is my Youtube post of my Multi-speed transmission I have called: "Opposing Torque Dynamic Clutch" which is a type of Infinitely Variable Transmission (IVT) which I believe is ideal for your current applications. Australian Patent Number: 2020201132. Please log on to my Youtube video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SACDK89U7PM In summary: It is a Compound Planetary System with two inputs from two separate electric motors. Motor 1 tries to rotate the carrier counter-clockwise and Motor 2 tries to rotate the carrier clockwise. The ratio, acceleration and speed of the vehicle is controlled by the amount and proportion of power/torque from the two motors. In addition the ratio of the transmission is affected by the speed and load of the vehicle. So, with the aid of speed sensors on all the components of the transmission, the speed of the vehicle, position of the accelerator and a kick-down switch - all that is needed to control the whole system is a computer. There is no actual gear selector for the driver to operate, however a manual mode would be appropriate where the driver has a 'balance' control knob that manually controls the proportion of power/torque to each motor and therefore can choose any ratio desired for the driving situation. An added enhancement could be added to the transmission by having a traditional planetary overdrive attached to each of the motors to enhance the rev range of each motor. This would enable the provision of extra modes like economy mode/sports mode and improve the kick-down mode by inputting more revs when the gearbox is in an extremely low ratio during kick-down operation. Having this type of transmission would improve acceleration and range of the vehicle allowing for a smaller battery pack/lighter weight leading to cost savings and simpler manufacturing. Its really about the particular city's infrastructure, if there are clear roads and bike lanes for PEVs to be used on they are fantastic. Here in Helsinki they were a bit chaotic at first, but etiquette has quickly developed around where they should be ridden, bike lanes and slow roads. Where to park, around metro stations, shopping malls and grocery stores, and when possible next to bike racks. Laws limit the rentable ones to a fastish jogging pace which while difficult to maintain on foot without getting winded still allows one to very safely bail on the scooter when hitting a pothole.

Only privately owned PEVs can go faster and helmets are highly encouraged all around. The rentable scooters seem to have fit in next to the pre-existing city sponsored shared bikes and a lot of the etiquette has crossed over. People actually carry helmets when intending to commute using one of these.

There are also clear laws around electrically powered vehicles and they very sensibly are given a power limit below which they may be used like bikes and above which they are only to be used on roads.

We are in the middle of a shift in transport culture, social norms and etiquette will only come with time, but hating on them because some people use them "for evil" so to speak is unreasonable.

PSU insurers offer car insurance in least premium and have best claim settlement. They usually charge almost 40-50% less than getting insurance from dealers. 
Claim settlement ratio is a vague concept to measure efficiency of an insurance company. You should instead focus on amount of claim settlement by companies. Pvt cos are known for settling small claim very swiftly and are notorious for denying (on any flimsy grounds) or under-settling big claims. So they can easily maintain good claim settlement ratio despite having far lesser amount settlement ratio.
PSUs have backing of govt and claim settlement is transparent and generous irrespective of the claim amount. They simple reason is: they have to strictly follow IRDAI guidelines and PSUs have social service as priority not brute profits. And now a days they match or even exceed the TAT( turn around time) compared to PVT companies. If you check the no of complaints against insurers in website of Ombudsman, Beema lokpal or IRDAI, private companies top the disgraceful list and govt companies are least tarnished.
Now,the question arises why dealers or online portals / web aggregators don't prefer PSUs
1) Huge commission paid by Pvt cos to dealers and online web aggregators. So, they sideline PSU insurers and charge hefty premiums from unsuspecting customers so that they can enjoy mammoth share of your premium as commission, totally flouting IRDAI rules.
2) The dealers and web aggregators have to scrupulously comply with IRDAI guidelines while dealing with PSU insurers which will reduce any foul play or   unfair practices which are meant for safeguarding customers against any fraud. Remember,if your claim is stuck by dealer or Pvt cos,you are nowhere to go but in govt companies, strict compliance saves any injustice. So dealers want monopoly in their hands not yours.
Thus, you can draw the inference as to why PSU insurers should the only choice while buying insurance for your loved vehicle.
The 4 renowned PSU/ Govt insurance companies are
1) UNITED INDIA INSURANCE CO. LTD
2) NEW INDIA ASSURANCE CO. LTD.
3) NATIONAL INSURANCE CO. LTD.
4) ORIENTAL INSURANCE CO. LTD.
So, next time you buy a new vehicle,never purchase insurance from dealer instead approach PSU office and get cover for your vehicle. And whenever you renew your cover, do the same .
Drive safe.

TLDR;

What are EV's?
EV's are essentially a pool of 512 points that you can invest in your pokemon's stats to increase them. You can only spend up to 252 points in a single stat.

Why are EV's important?
Using EV's to increase your stats is extremely important because it can lead to killing with moves that wouldn't normally kill, surviving moves that would normally kill, and outspeeding your oponent when you normally wouldn't.

How do I get EV train my pokemon?

Method 1 - the old fashioned way
Any wild pokemon that you knock out will award your team with EV points in a certain stat based on the wild pokemon. For example, a machoke will give your party 2 attack EV's. Once you know what EV's you want, find a pokemon that gives them on Cerebi, and go knock some out until you hit the desired EV points.

Method 2 - The baller way
You can buy vitamins with money or BP, and they each give 10 EV points in a specific stat.

Method 3 - Jobs
Sending pokemon on jobs will passively give them EV's. With full bonuses, maxing EV's in a stat takes 24 hours.

Speeding up the process
To speed up EV training, you can give your pokemon power items, purchasable for 10 BP. Holding a power item will add 5 EV's of a certain stat everytime you gain EV's.
You can also infect your pokemon with pokerus, which doubles the speed at which you gain EV's, stacking with power items.

How do I know how to spread my EV's?

Have they changed the EV cap per stat? For those who don't know, EVs before capped at 255 per stat and 510 total. However, if your EVs are not perfectly divisible by 4, then those remainder EVs will go to waste. With 510, you can only spare 2 extra EVs (510 -252 -252 -4 =2) without wasting any, so if you took a stat to the previous max, 255 then 255-252=3. 3 EVs would go to waste, and you'd miss a single stat point. While this may seem negligible, a single stat can make a world of a difference. It could garuntee or better your roll odds to OHKO or survive an attack that could OHKO, it could take you from being slower to a speed tie or a speed tie to outspeeding.
Anyway, rant aside, it's amazing that vitamins now carry you to 252 EVs, I just want to make sure that cap is for EVs period this generation, if that's just for vitamins, or if that's something that was missed.

I found that many times people are too lazy to properly fasten the battery post end attachments.  What end up happening is that the battery cable and it's clamp are  just tightened around the top and flush with the the battery post.  Since there is a slight slope on the battery post the battery post clamp cannot fully tightened around this battery terminal area.  To fix this simple mistake just take a small dowel and a hammer and tap the battery post clamp till it is flush with bottom of the battery post.  Then tighten the battery nut and bolt clamp at this wider battery post point.  this will give the battery post a much better fit and enable the battery's current to pass through the posts and terminals as easily as possible.....

I used to work for Ford back in the 80's and had Towncar come in every month with a dead battery. Never did find anything wrong with it and talked to the owner. He kept his auto lights adjusted all the way to the max so he could get into his house at night and only had the problem when he left his car at the airport when going on 1-2 week trips. I suggested he turn off his timer because the draw would weaken his battery and after sitting that long without starting it wouldn't recover from the draw. I never saw him again until the shop did service calls a few months later to see why he didn't return and told him forget my advise. The following week the car was back with the same problem and 3 other people looked at it and found nothing wrong. Shortly after that I went round & round with the service manager because he kept setting timing on a car using the mag riming notch and I told him that mark was only if you had a scope with the proper probe that there was another mark he had to use with a light and he told me I was stupid because he was a super master tech and knew everything, so I quit and went to work somewhere else where people actually knew what they were doing. Some people think just because they pass a test they know which end of a wrench to hold. At another shop I worked at They hired a new master tech and paid him way more than the rest of us who worked there for years and were also masters. He was just out of school and passed the test. His first car was a jeep no-start, he worked on it for a week replacing sensors and computer but all it would do was crank. We refused to help him because they wouldn't give us a raise or cut his pay down to our level. We knew what the problem was from day 1 but kept laughing at the know it all pro. After a week the manager asked us what we though and we all said why don't the pulleys turn when cranking? So he ended up putting a flywheel in it and it left. Shortly after he quit and we were all satisfied.

Our Chevy Tahoe had a parasitic drain. It was in the radio. The memory circuit that has continuous power even when the key was off. I pulled the radio fuse. Then found another fuse that only gets power when the key is on and ran a jumper wire from there to the radio fuse. So the radio only gets power when the key is on. The drawbacks are you can‚Äôt save presets because the memory is erased every time you turn the key off and the clock isn‚Äôt saved. We use a Bluetooth music device anyway so it‚Äôs no biggie.

That's a very F/U design with the batteries in the cab compartment.  We had an army 5 ton that had a generator overcharge the 4 huge 12 volt batteries that were in paired series/parallel, two banks of 12 volt parallel in series for a high amp 24 volt system.  We were on a 10 hour drive across Germany and didn't realize we were being gassed from the cooking batteries off gassing into the cab until we both started getting raw throats, coughing uncontrollably, screaming headaches and finally pulling over to puke our guts out.  When we felt like going back to the cab to check things out we noticed a steady stream of white cloud coming from the back of the cab body outside, it was the vent from the bench style battery compartment under the passenger/middle seat.  The motorpool mechanic said that the batteries were so hot, that they were still nearly boiling the next morning after the truck being towed to the nearest post and battery caps removed in the shop to check them.  They wound up waiting another 2 days letting them cool before removing them while they got the new replacement batteries and new generator replacement.  The older 5 ton trucks had generators instead of alternators that had to be "tuned" to the right output voltage with a hex key adjusting a trim potentiometer built into the generator.  The generator on our truck had this trim potentiometer go bad and no matter how it was adjusted it put out almost twice the voltage on a 24 volt system, hence the overcooked batteries.  The "vent on the back of the cab wall was an attempt to keep battery off gassing out of the cab and outside instead, it didn't work.

1. Rising supply pressure from China and Indonesia over the next couple of years
2. Tin-one of the worst performers on the LME so far this year~16% down
3. Constant miniaturisation of semiconductors equals less solder used as technology matures
4. Rising populism globally may mean even Namibia succumbs to failing rule of law. 
5. Industrial metals will not fair well if (and I believe we will) we have a short term credit cycle bust up.
There's my 2c worth, probably wrong but it's the way I see it. Long term, I like tin.
